[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "8877c3b313768ea6a3ed5c634060b917d30dd836b4dbc4d3de596e96bdbf32b0"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/trump_management"]
[Student "S"]
{East is to play 4\S. South leads the \CQ.

Losers:   \S=0  \H=3  \D=0  \C=1  Total = 4

You can't help the \C loser, but the \H loser can be ruffed in dummy. The most important question right now is how many rounds of trumps to pull before you give up a \H? 

None would be the correct answer. Suppose you decide to go over to dummy with the \SQ so as to lead a \H toward your \H Q 10 7. When South won the trick he would probably play another trump. Then when you gave up a second \H dummy's final trump might be removed.

Win the first trick and play a \H from your hand. If they play a \S, win in your hand and play another \H. If they play another \S it will be just the second and dummy will still have one \S left to ruff your \H loser.

At the first hint that you might be thinking of ruffing losers in dummy the defenders are going to start leading trumps to try to prevent you.

So you must stay a jump ahead of them. In this Deal the only way they could have gotten the jump on you would have been with a trump opening lead.}
[Play "W"]CQ

